        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "What Are Reflexive Verbs?",
        "content": "Reflexive verbs describe actions you do TO YOURSELF. The action reflects back on the subject. In Spanish, they're marked with 'se' at the end of the infinitive."
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "Reflexive Pronouns",
        "content": "These pronouns show WHO the action reflects back on:\n                              → se = themselves/yourselves (ellos/ustedes)",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "me",
            "english": "myself (yo)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "te",
            "english": "yourself (tú)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "se",
            "english": "himself/herself/yourself formal"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "nos",
            "english": "ourselves (nosotros)"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "se",
            "english": "themselves/yourselves (ellos/ustedes)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "LEVANTARSE (to get up)",
        "content": "The pronoun goes BEFORE the conjugated verb:\n                              \n   ✏️ Exercise: Yo ___ levanto a las siete.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "spanish": "yo me levanto",
            "english": "I get up"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "tú te levantas",
            "english": "you get up"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "él/ella se levanta",
            "english": "he/she gets up"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "nosotros nos levantamos",
            "english": "we get up"
          },
          {
            "spanish": "ellos se levantan",
            "english": "they get up"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "lesson",
        "heading": "Common Reflexive Verbs",
